<h4>
    Comet Basics
</h4>

<ul>
    <li>
        Comets are balls of dust, rock, and ice.
    </li>
    <li>
        Comets remain inside the solar system.
        Most of the time, comets are in the farthest away areas of the solar system: the Kuiper Belt
        and the Oort Cloud.
    </li>
    <li>
        Comets stay away from the sun for many years, then very quickly swing around the sun.
        Their orbit is highly elliptical, with the sun at one focus of the ellipse.
        We say that, relative to circular orbits, the orbit of a comet has a very high <emph>eccentricity</emph>.
    </li>
    <li>
        When comets swing around the sun, they appear to humans for a few brief weeks.
        Then, they return to the Kuiper Belt or Oor Cloud for many years.
    </li>
</ul>

<h4>
    Comet Tails
</h4>
<ul>
    <li>
        Comets only have a <emph>tail</emph> when they are near the sun,
        the rest of the time, they are just a ball.
    </li>
    <li>
        The <emph>tail</emph> appears because ice is melting and flying off the comet as they are near the sun.
    </li>
    <li>
        Comets do not fly across the sky. Like everything else in the solar system,
        they appear in different points of the sky each night, in a pattern that makes sense
        only if you look at the solar system as a whole.
    </li>
    <li>
        The tail is <strong>NOT</strong> behind the comet.
        The direction of the tail is always pointing away from the sun,
        irrespective of what direction the comet is moving.
    </li>
</ul>

