<h4>
    Comet Orbit Energy
</h4>

<ul>
    <li>
        As the comet moves around the sun,
        it has a constant amount of energy.
        This energy exchanges between kinetic energy gravitational
        potential energy as the comet orbits the sun;.
    </li>
    <li>
        The comet moves <emph>faster</emph> when it is <strong>close</strong> to the sun
        and <emph>slower</emph> when it is <strong>far away</strong> from the sun.
        Whenever it is moving faster, it has more kinetic energy.
    </li>
    <li>
        When the comet is farther away from the sun,
        the comet**  has <strong>more</strong> gravitational potential energy.
        When the comet is closer to the sun, it has <strong>less</strong>
        gravitational potential energy.
    </li>
</ul>

<p>
    **Technically, gravitational potential energy is held not by the comet
    but by the system containing both the comet and the sun.
    This issue is explored in depth in <a href = '/pod/bf8c2f'>another pod</a>,
    and the precise language is used in all pods level 3 and above.
</p>

